qas.question: What percent of normal matter is hydrogen?
What percent of atoms is hydrogen?
What 2 forms of mass is most of the universe consisted of?

context: Hydrogen, as atomic H, is the most abundant chemical element in the universe, making up <a0_0>75%<a0_0/> of normal matter by mass and over <a1_0>90%<a1_0/> by number of atoms (most of the mass of the universe, however, is not in the form of chemical-element type matter, but rather is postulated to occur as yet-undetected forms of mass such as <a2_0>dark matter and dark energy<a2_0/>). This element is found in great abundance in <a3_0>stars<a3_0/> and gas giant planets. Molecular clouds of H2 are associated with star formation. Hydrogen plays a vital role in powering stars through the proton-proton reaction and the CNO cycle nuclear fusion.
